SECTION F - FIFO WAIT EXAMPLE (EARLY TIMELINE)
----------------------------------------------
FIFO preserves the raw input order, so some long low-priority Ward jobs occupy
capacity before later urgent tasks arrive.

Initial FIFO dispatch order is simply Task 1 to Task 9.

| Robot | First picked task | Target Zone | t = 0 result |
|-------|-------------------|-------------|--------------|
| robot-1 | Task 1 | ICU | Starts immediately (ICU slot 1/2) |
| robot-2 | Task 2 | Ward | Starts immediately (Ward slot 1/2) |
| robot-3 | Task 3 | OR | Starts immediately (OR slot 1/1) |
| robot-4 | Task 4 | Ward | Starts immediately (Ward slot 2/2) |
| robot-5 | Task 5 | ICU | Starts immediately (ICU slot 2/2) |
| robot-6 | Task 6 | OR | WAITS because OR is already full |
| robot-7 | Task 7 | ICU | WAITS because ICU is already full |
| robot-8 | Task 8 | ICU | WAITS because ICU is already full |
| robot-9 | Task 9 | ICU | WAITS because ICU is already full |

FIFO early wait chain
---------------------
- t = 0 s: 5 robots working, 4 robots waiting
- t = 3 s: Task 3 finishes, OR opens, robot-6 starts Task 6
- t = 4 s: Task 1 finishes, ICU opens, robot-7 starts Task 7
- t = 5 s: Task 5 still running until 5 s, so ICU pressure remains high
- after ICU frees again, robot-8 and then robot-9 can finally begin
- Long Ward blockers (Task 2 and Task 4) remain active for 12 s and 9 s,
  so later Ward work cannot start even though robots may already be free.

FIFO demo message
-----------------
FIFO is easy to explain, but it allows long early low-priority jobs to occupy
critical zone slots, which causes visible waiting for later urgent work.


SECTION G - PRIORITY WAIT EXAMPLE (EARLY TIMELINE)
--------------------------------------------------
Priority reorders all High tasks before Normal and Low tasks.

That helps urgent completion, but in this stress example it also clusters many
robots onto the same scarce ICU / OR zones at the same time.

Approximate first Priority queue prefix:
	1, 3, 6, 9, 11, 13, 16, 19, 21, ...

Zone pattern of that prefix:
	ICU, OR, OR, ICU, OR, ICU, ICU, ICU, OR

Immediate result at t = 0 s:
	- ICU can run only 2 of those tasks
	- OR can run only 1 of those tasks
	- Ward sits idle at first because almost no early job uses it
	- So only 3 robots start immediately and 6 robots wait

Priority early wait snapshot
----------------------------
| Resource state at t = 0 s | Value |
|---------------------------|-------|
| ICU running tasks | 2 / 2 |
| OR running tasks | 1 / 1 |
| Ward running tasks | 0 / 2 |
| Robots actively working | 3 / 9 |
| Robots waiting on zone capacity | 6 / 9 |

Priority demo message
---------------------
Priority usually wins for urgent tasks, but under strong zone bottlenecks it can
also create a "traffic jam" by concentrating too many workers on the same scarce
zones at the same time.


SECTION H - SRT WAIT EXAMPLE (EARLY TIMELINE)
---------------------------------------------
SRT-like ordering pushes the shortest jobs first.

In this workload, the shortest jobs are mostly the 3 s OR jobs and 4 s ICU jobs.
That means SRT also concentrates early demand on the OR and ICU bottlenecks.

Typical earliest SRT candidates:
	- Task 3 (OR, 3 s)
	- Task 11 (OR, 3 s)
	- Task 21 (OR, 3 s)
	- Task 29 (OR, 3 s)
	- Task 39 (OR, 3 s)
	- then 4 s ICU jobs such as Task 1 / 9 / 13 / 19 / 27 / 31 / 37

Immediate SRT effect
--------------------
	- OR fills instantly with one 3 s task
	- several other OR tasks must wait behind it
	- ICU fills with short urgent jobs
	- Ward is underused in the first instant

But after the first few seconds, SRT tends to free bottleneck slots quickly,
because its earliest zone occupants are short jobs rather than long blockers.

SRT strong-wait takeaway
------------------------
	- Initial waiting can be very high because many 3 s / 4 s tasks target OR / ICU
	- But average completion time may still look best because those short tasks clear
	  scarce slots faster than FIFO or Priority's long blockers

SRT demo message
----------------
SRT may produce high initial waiting at the bottlenecked zones, but it often
reduces average completion time because short jobs clear those scarce slots fast.


SECTION I - ROUND ROBIN WAIT EXAMPLE (4 s QUANTUM)
--------------------------------------------------
Round Robin starts from arrival order like FIFO, so its first queue wave looks
similar to FIFO:
	- 5 robots start immediately
	- 4 robots wait at t = 0 s

What makes RR different is what happens after long jobs begin occupying scarce
zones. Instead of letting a long task dominate the visible comparison timeline,
the demo view slices execution into 4 s chunks.

That means RR is useful for explaining:
	- fairness,
	- repeated turn-taking,
	- and why long zone-heavy jobs do not visually dominate the schedule the same
	  way they do under plain FIFO.

RR demo message
---------------
Round Robin does not remove the zone bottleneck, but it makes the contention more
balanced and easier to visualize because long jobs are broken into smaller pieces.


SECTION J - COMPARISON TALKING POINTS FOR A DEMO
------------------------------------------------
1. FIFO
	- Starts 5 robots immediately and 4 wait immediately
	- Long early low-priority jobs can block Ward / ICU capacity
	- Easy to explain but inefficient for urgent work under bottlenecks

2. Priority
	- Finishes urgent tasks earlier
	- But may create the biggest first-second waiting spike, because many urgent
	  jobs compete for the same scarce ICU / OR capacity at once

3. SRT
	- Also clusters short jobs into scarce zones at the start
	- But those jobs finish quickly, so zone slots free sooner
	- Usually best for average completion time in a congested system

4. Round Robin
	- Similar initial wait pattern to FIFO
	- Better fairness / visualization for long tasks
	- Good for showing turn-taking behavior under contention


